observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Municipal Accountant should submit an explanation to the Audit Team why liquidated damages were not imposed on the contractor for incurring unreasonable delays in the execution of the contract.
We also recommended that the Municipal Engineer and the Municipal Planning and Development Officer should:
submit the duly approved Suspension Orders/Extension Orders, and the likes, so that a new contract duration can be computed and verified if still in conformity with contract period 120 calendar days, and liquidated damage can be imposed, if any;
ensure the timely and immediate completion of planned projects for the year;
include anticipated unworkable days in estimating the number of days to complete a project to come up with a realistic project duration;
conduct regular monitoring and supervision in the implementation of the projects;
proper document any the time extension and/or suspension of works of the projects; and
impose liquidated damages on payments to contractors pursuant to Item 9.1 of Annex “E” of the 2016 Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184.

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant should submit the lacking procurement documents and a justification why payments were made despite the lacking documents;
We also recommended that the BAC should require all suppliers under the Emergency Procurement of the Bayanihan Act, to execute an OSS with the stipulations provided in Appendix 1 of GPPB Circular 01-2020; and
Henceforth, management should comply with pertinent requirements before payment is made to avoid audit suspensions/disallowance.

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant shall:

Trace the monthly variances in the Due to BIR account on remittances against taxes withheld in CY 2019 and prior years, and prepare adjustments, where necessary;

Remit to the BIR all taxes withheld to avoid surcharges, penalties and interest that maybe imposed by said agency; 

Prepare the Disbursement Voucher due to the BIR for the remittance of creditable taxes, simultaneous when DVs are made for payments to suppliers and contractors to ensure its remittance;

Prepare an adjusting entry to correct the erroneous recording totaling ₱145,165.26; and

Review the work of the accounting staff to avoid errors.  

We also recommended that the Municipal Treasurer shall submit to the Municipal Accountant every 10th day of the month the disbursement vouchers, payrolls and monthly reports on the transactions of the LGU in order to update the recording in the books of the LGU.

